events.description: The release of the services sector purchasing managers' index for China in January 2026.

facts.fact_text: The RatingDog China General Services PMI rose to 52.3 in January 2026, exceeding the market expectation of 51.8.

evidences.evidence_text: The RatingDog China General Services PMI increased to 52.3 in January 2026 from December’s six-month low of 52.0, surpassing market expectations of 51.8.

facts.fact_text: Service sector firms in China increased their staffing levels for the first time since July.

evidences.evidence_text: In response to the rise in new orders, firms increased staffing for the first time since last July.

facts.fact_text: The rate of cost inflation for service firms reached a five-month low.

evidences.evidence_text: However, the rate of cost inflation eased to a five-month low.

claims.claim_text: Business sentiment in the services sector has weakened due to concerns about global economic growth.
claims.author: RatingDog

evidences.evidence_text: Looking ahead, business sentiment weakened to below the average level seen in 2025 amid rising concerns over the outlook for global economic growth.

evidence.evidence_text: The latest reading marked the strongest expansion in the services sector since last October, driven by stronger growth in new orders
In response to the rise in new orders, firms increased staffing for the first time since last July.
On prices, input costs continued to rise, driven by higher prices for purchased items and fuel.
rising concerns over the outlook for global economic growth.
